description:
“THE GIFT OF DOOM!” Roger Steele is given a diamond by an unnamed man and told it has a curse that may doom him. He is unable to throw it away without it returning, but it is finally stolen, and the thief is killed by it.

As the Comics Code Authority's strict upkeep began coming into question in the late 1960's, editor Joe Orlando decided that the "House of Mystery" was in need of renovation. So, he pulled up the floorboards that had been worn out by super hero adventures over the past several years and refurbished the series to its horror anthology roots.

Contents

  • The Gift of Doom (from House of Mystery #137)
  • All Alone
  • Cain's Game Room
  • The House of Gargoyles

description:
“SOUR NOTE.” A man wonders about the history of the estate he occupies, and a ghost appears to reveal that he ‘murdered’ himself (and assumed a new identity) in order to avoid reprisal for claim jumping.

"The man who murdered himself" in this issue of House of Mystery was Marv Wolfman's first horror yarn and the first DC story illustrated by Berni Wrightson (who left the "e" off his name to distinguish himself from a famous diver.) In the story, narrated by "caretaker" Cain, an estate in 1882 was haunted by the ghost of a man who killed himself. Fans of the comic didn't know it, but they were witnessing the earliest effort of two greats who would become renowned for their tales of terror and suspense.

  • Sour Note
  • Cain's True Case Files: The Man Who Murdered Himself
  • Page 13
  • Cain's Game Room
  • The Widow's Walk
  • Cain's True Case Files: The Dead Tell Tales

A doctor becomes jealous of the gardener, so he murders him with an ax. When his wife proclaims innocence, he repents and makes the body the recipient of the first plastic artificial brain. He replaces the wife's brain and plans to do so with the doctor as well in order to begin building a new army of perfect thinkers.

description:
George Ringler is on death row for a murder he didn’t commit. Caspar Creed uses his fortune to find a magical artifact to give him back his youth.

"The Demon Within!"

A boy named Gary Winters discovered that by some form of magic, he can transform himself into a red monster and return to his normal self. He is not viscious as the monster but frightens his parents and sister, then his schoolmates and teachers with this ability. They don’t understand the boy's ability and insist that he stop transforming himself into this red monster. His parents take him to a hospital for tests. The doctor asks for a week to study the child and determine if anything is possible to prevent the child from transforming himself into a monster. The doctor determines that the boy can transform himself by thinking, so the doctor performs a lobotomy on the boy. Following the operation, the boy becomes a blankly staring and unthinking child. The community feels safe again, but horrific damage was done to the child forever.

Contents

  1. "Welcome to the House of Mystery" written by Joe Orlando, penciled and inked by Bernie Wrightson.
  2. "Put Your Trust in a Killer!" written by Steve Skeates, penciled and inked by Adolfo Buylla.
  3. "Million-Dollar Magic" Reprinted from House of Mystery #60.
  4. "Cain's Game Room" written, penciled and inked by Sergio Aragones.
  5. "Hail the Conquering Aliens" Reprinted from House of Mystery #103.
  6. "The Demon Within!" plotted by Joe Orlando, scripted by John Albano, penciled and inked by Jim Aparo. Reprinted in Limited Collectors Edition C-52, DC Special Blue Ribbon Digest #24, Wrath of the Spectre #4 and Welcome Back to the House of Mystery #1.
  7. "A Tale of Vengeance!" written by John Albano, penciled and inked by Sam Glanzman.

Notes: All original stories reprinted in Showcase Presents: House of Mystery #2.

description:
1. "Ruby!" written by J. M. DeMatteis, penciled and inked by Noly Zamora, lettered by Esphidy and colored by Tatjana Wood.
  2. "The King and the Dragon!" written by Bud Simons, penciled by Keith Giffen, inked by John Celardo, lettered by Shelly Leferman and colored by Tatjana Wood.
  3. "Friends to the End" written by Bill Kelley, penciled and inked by Jun Lofamia, lettered by Unknown and colored by Bob LeRose.
  4. "Deadly Peril at 20,000!" written by Carl Wessler, penciled and inked by Jess Jodloman, lettered by Unknown and colored by Bob LeRose.

description:
“I… VAMPIRE!” Andrew Bennett is a vampire hunter who hunts down vampires from the Cult of the Blood Red Moon alongside his allies, Deborah Dancer, and Dmitri Mishkin. How will they fare when they face Mary Seward, The Queen of Blood?!

Story Titles

  • I... Vampire!
  • An Exercise in Fear
  • Special Defects

Notes:

  • This issue is the beginning of the regular I, Vampire feature.
  • The cover is a homage to the cover of Baffling Mysteries #7.

“BLOOD TIES!” Having faked his own death, Andrew Bennett wanders the roads of Kansas, feeding on farm animals. He begins to realize that he's losing his taste for animals and will soon require human blood! Plus, “HOUSE ODDS” and “D-DAY FOR EARTH!”

Contents

  1. I... Vampire! Chapter Seven: Blood Ties!
  2. House Odds
  3. D-Day for Earth
  4. Benny's Friend

Notes:

  • The cover is a homage to the cover of Baffling Mysteries #7.

description:
1. Hop On the Welfare Wagon!: (public service message from Superman) A man tells Mr. Stanton that Superman will speak for their hospital fundraiser. He responds "Who needs a hospital in this town? I can take care of myself. I'm not giving a red cent, Superman or no Superman." Just then, Superman shows up saying he "has the wrong slant" and explaining that Americans have always helped each other when sickness and trouble came.
  2. The Man With the Evil Eye!: (by Ruben Moreira) Blinded by cornea damage from a gun exploding in his face, a gangster named Jim Keene moves to a superb across state lines to lay low. after he learns his neighbor has willed his corneas to him in the event of his death, Jim arranges an accident. Once he can see again he bumps into a man on the street and after a brief argument, the man dies of a heart attack while ranting about Jim's evil eye. Jim dismisses the idea but the papers play up ie idea that he can kill with a look. he then meets a girl at a club and falls in love but when she tells him she is having dinner with another man he gets angry, yelling at her and she too has a heart attack renting about his evil eye. Panicked, he runs to the doctor demanding he take the eye out, and when the doctor tells him to come back tomorrow he declares he killed a guy for this eye. It is then revealed that both deaths were faked in an elaborate ruse to get him to confess to murder.
  3. River of Death: legend about a river that people believe no one who falls in can escape alive.
  4. Friday the 13th Club: A shopkeeper and a cabby start a club to change superstitions.
  5. Nightmare: A man is dreaming about people dying and the dreams are coming true.
  6. Knightly Ghost!:
  7. Spectre of Death!:
  8. Phantom Ships: (a text story)
  9. His Double-- In Doom?:
